04285nam a22005175i 9780774852364DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071998xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748523647 a10.59962/97807748523642doi  a(DE-B1597)661503  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD8110.C352bB74 1998eb 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a331.8/097123/381 aBright, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Limits of Labour :bClass Formation and the Labour Movement in Calgary, 1883-1929 /cDavid Bright. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (286 p.) :b13 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tClass Formation, 1883–1913 -- tFrom Cow Town to Hub of Industry -- tSocial Divisions and Class Disposition -- tClass, Culture, and Politics -- tUnions and Strikes -- tThe Labour Movement, 1913–29 -- tDepression and War, 1913–7 -- tEconomic Recession and Restructuring, 1918–24 -- t1919: Revolt Reconsidered -- tDissent and Descent: Labour Politics in Calgary, 1918–24 -- tThe Limits of Labour, 1925–9 -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a few short decades before the First World War, Calgary was transformed from a frontier outpost into a complex industrial metropolis. With industrialization there emerged a diverse and equally complex working class. David Bright explores the various levels of class formation and class identity in the city to argue that Calgary's reputation as a prewar centre of labour conservatism is in need of revision. Bright also delineates the trials of the Calgary labour movement in the 1920s. Internal divisions and dissent prevented the movement from realizing the potential strength of the working class. Instead, even as local capitalism restructured itself, political and industrial labour organizations wilfully fragmented their own base of support. In particular, they failed to address the concerns and needs of the growing number of unemployed in the city, a neglect that foreshadowed events of the 1930s. This failure left the labour movement unable to meet the challenge of the Great Depression. In part, at least, the demise of labour as a viable political alternative in Calgary paved the way for the rise of Social Credit. Using Calgary as a model, The Limits of Labour reasserts the need to place class formation at the heart of the development of western Canada and provides an historical context to the renewed struggle of labour for social justice in the 1990s.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485236440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774852364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774852364/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles